segments.text: We opted, you know, back in the 70s to someday keep the boundaries around the Woodlands so that it cannot be a separate subdivision.
That's very important, a separate political subdivision, you know, in the town, because it has to answer Houston's need.
That was the whole philosophy at the beginning of the philosophy.
Mr. Mitchell, let's start back, if you will, and tell us, if you think the Woodlands has built out as you anticipated that it would,
20 years ago or so when you began this project.
Well, I would say this as far as what we hear from the people and whether it has done very well.
I talk to people all the time because we live out here, and they're sincere.
They say, I've been here eight years now, and I want to tell you it's the best place I've ever lived.
I mean, hundreds of people tell me that, and I don't think they do it just to bother me out.
They do it because they're sincere about it.
And what do they point to?
I would say this, that the...

The fact that we're probably behind schedule something you've had, but three high-energy, not high-energy, but also high-interest peaks that slows down production of the crash of Houston in the last six, seven years.
When we first opened in 74, the interest rates had gone through the ceiling.
I'll just give you, we went through about three cycles of high-interest rates, the crash of Houston.
But in spite of all that, the wooden has done very well.
But I'd say we're
You know, we're behind our schedule.
We thought we'd probably be 45,000 people.
By now, we're 32,000 people.
So we're doing quite well.
So in terms of physical size, it's not where you really anticipated being.
In terms of pace, it's not exactly where we originally thought it would be.
But as far as the quality and as far as doing well from a land development standpoint, it's profitable on land development.
On our capital structure, on office buildings and apartments, it'll take a while for those to be
profitable on cash flow basis, and they looked very promising.
So I think that, in general, the Woodlands have done very well.
In fact, I have to say that, you know, I've always studied all new towns in the world.

I went to Europe, I looked at France, I looked at England, I had Dick Brown go to Capiola, I'd go to Sweden, I looked at the West Coast, I looked at the East Coast, Columbia, I took some of the people from Columbia, some of the people from
from Irvine and merged them in because there was no one in Houston originally knew the magnitude of that project.
Columbia was the second generation of Newtown.
Levittown was the first generation of Newtown.
And we're the third generation over Columbia.
And I would say this, that we're pulling it off, I think, quite well.
In fact, it's unique in the country, in my opinion.
If you look at all major projects in the country,
None of them have done the entire fabric that we have put together between the social structure, the environmental structure, and maybe the economic structure.
Irvine is much better economically.
Is it?
Irvine's done very well, but the land cost was very low.
I think Goldberg of New York Times, he really criticized it about a year ago.
That's the argument, Goldberg.
Because it's just a sea of roost.
Here, you go right through the wilderness, 32,000 people, you don't see anything.
What we did to preserve the natural appearance of the wilderness was, I think, was rather unusual.
And then how do you really environmentally do that and still make a profit?
That's a tough one.
Right, that's the trick.
In other words, I could crash every tree down and turn around and get more lots or get more office building, but that isn't what we do.
We try to design with nature.
We try to design the social structure with each other, and we try to have to make a profit out of it.
And I'd say this is coming along well.

If I looked at all the projects in the country, look at Reston, Virginia, Columbia, Maryland, Irvine, Westlake, all the ones on the west coast, all the HUD projects, which none of them have really been, that have made it except the Woodlands, that had no default.
I would say that this should stand out, in my opinion, as something unusual and unique.
Now, how do we convince
the world, that's what it is.
And how do they gain on what we have done?
Which is why I have you people working on this.
How do you really document this so other people can do the same thing on the next generation?
To go through our case history, which we wrote the first book, as you know.
And therefore, we're trying to get the factual information over the next 10 years of what it was since the first book.
How that was put out.
You're documenting that.
We're also doing a picture essay on the Woodlands now, which is different than what you're doing.
And then after you finish your
factual study.

What I'll do is to get maybe some other writers to go back from the beginning and do it on a combined documentary, but really have a flowing language that relates to a little different approach to it.
You see what I mean?
Sure.
That's what I think we should do.
Because the picture essay could be a coffee table thing for all families in the world or wherever else, you know, credentials or whatever it is.
The other one is really what you, the first book and the second book that you're doing, or the facts you're getting together, really gives you how this was done.
And is it successful?
And with all the warts that you can find and all the pluses that you can find, you see.
What are the warts and the pluses that you see right now?
Well, I would say there's a lot of warts.
I think that it's extremely difficult financially to make these things work.
And I think this, that...
that if you don't have the holding power or staying power and you don't show profit the first 10 years cash flow, most corporations won't take it.
They won't take it.
They won't look at the mid-term, long-term like we're looking at it.
They look at it too short-term, next quarter, next year, next two years, and they won't take them on.
I think that if it's successful over a long period of time, that it does have a good rate of return, which I think it will have, then more major
whatever it is, pension funds, corporations, insurance companies, might take them on as investment.
Now, the rest has been taken over by mobile.
It went through three ringers of being more or less in the bankruptcy.
So they're doing real well.
They're happy with the rest of it.
So the real key to a new community is the finance structure behind it.
I would say that is the most difficult thing to do, financing and getting it, and knowing that it's a long waiting period to see that the cash flow turns around.
Irvine could do it quicker because they own the land that started with the Pitch, Cincinnati.
We had to buy the land at higher cost, you see, and most other people do, too.
But I think that's the most difficult.
Then, of course, there's always the complications of

here we turn around the woodlands and we we've got we've got environmental impact study with the first one ever done by hud and we designed our roads and all our things and built an enormous infrastructure for the future and now they come back and say oh too bad now we're going to look at environmental impact again by pieces yeah see that's really disturbing oh we got a new uh wetlands ordinance that's coming out now that stops your development here in fact all of houston we're doing pretty well because we did have an early impact in
And they're a little bit more liberal with us, but Houston's in trouble unless they get the law changed on what is wetlands, you see.
Those retroactive type things really are very, very serious for developers to think about.
My gosh, they just spend several hundred million dollars on roads and infrastructure and everything, and they change the rules on you.
Those are the dangers we have.
Then, we've done very well with the city of Houston, because we're in their external jurisdiction.
We've done very well with the Montgomery County, because we're getting more and more commercial people here, because we've been working good tax abatements and things with Montgomery County.
And that political strain is pretty well eased?
The original strain was very stiff.
Since then, they realize that Woodland's their future tax base.
And they're working with it.
And the school's working with it.
So that's working good.
We're able to get the toll road up.
It was extremely important.
As you know, it was very important.
But you see, we're convinced
The city, if you didn't get to the airport, why spend a billion on the airport?
You couldn't get there.
I mean, how are you going to get to the airport?
Are they going to go in a helicopter?
So, therefore, Lindsay, if I wouldn't do it, Lindsay would step in and do it.
The total was really to serve all of North.
Harris County and Montgomery County.
It wasn't just for the women.
It just so happened to come right by here because we're on the way.
So, it's extremely important.
I think that the...
The various things in the River Authority we work with have been very well on our water systems and our source treatment plant systems.
We've really had really great cooperation with entities like that.
The federal regulations that come back retroactive are the most serious thing that would cause large developments to worry about whether you can get it done.
And that's what you're going to be working with and against in the future.
And yet we think we can work it out, because we do have, we designed it that way to start with.
kept 7,000 acres of wood claims that we wouldn't touch out of 25,000 acres.
One thing that we did do is to really preserve the forest.
It's rather interesting.
The original concept is how you design a forest and end up with 150,000 people and not destroy it.
Now, that's a very difficult thing to do.
And I think that so far it's working very well.
And we keep the natural.
You drive around the woods, you don't understand.
We don't have a bunch of manicured lawns and a bunch of all the freeways manicured, a bunch of flowers all over the place.
It's all the natural.
One thing we've run into, incidentally, is that you're having to educate the people who live here how to live.
That's right.
See, every home that comes in here, we give them a booklet.
Have you seen the booklet?
The new booklet?
They've got a very nice booklet.
You're talking about a very sensitive subject to me, George.
The lot next to me was just cleared yesterday.
That's another...
They cleared it?
Yeah.
Well, who was the builder?
Lee.
Who?
Bill Lee.
Well, why don't you get a hold of our design committee and kick their butts?
As far as I can tell, everything they do... Did they clear a lot of the trees?
It's practically...
They're building to the lot line...
That's your design committee.
You've got some input from the community association.
Raise hell with them.
I'm going to raise hell.
All right.
But you've got to do it before it happens.
It's too late.
I know, but then, no, I think that you've got to raise hell or it won't happen again, Joe.
You're a guinea pig, Joe.
Sorry.
How do you build that infrastructure, though, that can keep this kind of world and value system going?
Very difficult.
We fight hard for the trees.
We raise hell with this wall market, clearly, and yet
There's no doubt when you develop, you're going to cause some damage to the trees.
There's no doubt about it.

But I'll say this, that I think we've done, considering you see 32,000 people and you can't already see them in the buildings, we've done a remarkable job, even though we have some like Joey, and that's something we've got to get into, Joe, to see why it happened and to get a better control of that.
So I get upset about it, too, because I go around a lot and I see things, and I think that it's very important to do that.
But the Greenland people, they don't understand why they read like the Woodlands.
They come out here and live, because we have hiking bike trails everywhere, you know.
And we have, we designed the roads for 150,000 people to start with.
And we designed the overpass, which costs us some trees.
I don't want to do that, but then you've got that trade-off.
I mean, I would get one to grow in the middle, and I hate to do it, because it's going to lose that beautiful layer of trees I'm going to lose.
Or some of them.
So I think we have to really figure out how you have the feeling of my own people
You fight hard to do your design accordingly, and that's very difficult.
Forget about the buyer.
He doesn't know better, apparently.
But there are people who now have to train the 24 builders.
Their superintendents don't do it, and in fact, they're not supposed to cut any tree down that was six inches at all.
If they did, Joe, you ought to raise hell without permission.
If they did, I want to know about it.
You tell me about it.
Well, you couldn't put the house there if the tree's there.
Well, I admit that some thing is right in the middle of a lot to do something.
But there's some things that you could do something by changing your location around and miss some of those things.
But however, it's a very difficult thing to urbanize and think you're going to keep it completely pristine.
You can't do that.
So you have to know there's some trade-offs.
But what people don't realize about the Woodlands
They drive around.
They don't understand why it's so strikingly beautiful, because of the natural look.
And you have buildings that reflect the trees on the side of the building.
You have natural landscaping around the building.
You don't have a bunch of flowers around the building.
A few places of color, we have a few places.
But even then, we work on them.
So I think that is important.
The thing is, the social structure is important.
Economic base is very important.
So how do you put it all together?
We have schools.
We have great schools that work hard with the Conway School District.
With the private school, the Cooper Private School, we're funding the U of H out here now.
We've got community college ready to come out here now.
We have the high tech.
We've got about 1,200 scientists and assistants over there now in the high tech area.
That's beginning to evolve.
If you get up to 5,000, it'll be a critical mass.
We're finally convincing A&M and all them they ought to get involved in the Woodlands, because that's where the action's going to be through HARC.
And they're beginning to come alive.
It's all part of history.
Southwest, Texas, and the nation.
And therefore, this could be a role model.
I've looked at Kingwood and First Colony and Clear Lake.
They're nice.
But they're not like the Woodlands.
Could you expand on one of the things you just said?
One of the things, the strategic initiatives in the Woodlands that is little understood because it's very subtle, is the...
the obvious, at least obvious to me, effort that you've gone to to develop an industrial, commercial background as well as the residential.
The residential, you know... See, our objective, 150,000 people here eventually, in 30 or 40 years from now, is to have 100,000 jobs, maybe more.
And that's important.
I'm not a suburb.
I'm not a little subdivision.
We're really, we're not a new town, because we've got to be part of the whole, part of Houston.

And that's why we opted that Houston, see, in 72, Houston did not, they barely had what they call a five-mile extraterritorial jurisdiction, and they barely touched our south end, barely five miles from the city limits.
I had the choice of saying, okay, we'll make a separate political subdivision up here, or be part of Houston.
Well, philosophically,
I don't think you can feed off the airport, off the infrastructure fusion, off the port, and not be part of the whole.
If the talent that flees to the suburbs, in fact, the Woodlands concept was put together for that reason.
In the 60s, when I went to, I saw Bedford-Stuyvesant in New York.
I saw Watts.
And the concern is that, how do you urbanize better?
How do we do it better?
Or are you going to have, like, Los Angeles and Washington have these 100 political subdivisions
Strangling the central core where it can't manage itself?
Or can you make it be part of the whole?
The town of Woodlands better make Houston work.
Because you're going to be part of Houston.
Because the brain drain and the tax drain goes to the suburbs.
Is that working the way you thought it would, though, the Houston-Woodlands connection?
One thing I haven't been able to do yet is to build the whole cross-section of the socioeconomic and ethnic mix.
And I won't for 40 years.
And it'll never be 35%.
black and 35% Hispanic.
It'll probably be 15%, 10-15% black and 10-15% Hispanic.
I'm just giving you what I think we're having 40 years from now.
So you don't make the social ethnic mix that you think, or economic mix.
However, we had up to about three years ago, 14% run assist people in the woods.
Now in the last three years with all these cheap houses that went on RTC,
A lot of people bought these $60,000 condominiums for $30,000, and we didn't get them up here because there's no market up here.
But now we're getting back to thinking about townhouses and cluster houses and getting a medium range.
It used to be about $68,000 per medium house.
Now it's up to $120,000, and I don't like that.
I'm trying to bring it down again by starting now that those things have dried up, go back into townhouses and cluster houses to build a lower end.
When I used to get rent assistance from HUDS,

programs I was able to build some more because one thing we did here in the Wilmington very unusual is the design of the Wilmington itself you can't take a $40,000 house and put a million dollar house next door it won't work I don't care what the social scientists tell you it might work it won't work so we designed what you call the Pollyanna effort that's where you took a $40,000 to $70,000 house it's 30, 40 in this cul-de-sac
and a layer of trees, and then you put the semi to $100,000 houses, a layer of trees, and so on, until you find you've got a billion-dollar house.
Every village has a whole cross-section.
And they all go to the same school, same shopping area.
Now, that's the concept of the woodland that we're able to put out because we're able to use the forest to help us do that.
And that's the concept that I'm trying to work here.
Now, I would say this.
My median price has gone up higher than I'd like to see it.
I'm trying to push it down now that the RTC has stopped all these give-away sales, where then we can do it.
Because our value stayed pretty good for once.
And all this downturn, our value may have lost 8% to 10%, not 30%, 40%.
And they already bounced back and created big demand for sales of used houses at this time, and resale houses now.
Because the values have been here.
That's one thing that has changed.
Houston would buy a house in every little subdivision around the town.
They don't do that anymore.
Well, we had in 1982 about 2% of the Houston market.

We now have 8.5% of the Houston market, because they feel the security is here, the quality of life is here, the job opportunity is here, the access to Houston is very good, and therefore we have a great impact on the whole urbanization process.
And there, when Houston gets to be, the key is, when Houston gets to be 6 million people, which it will be,
How do we do it better?
That's the whole concept of the woodlands.
Is that percentage holding up for jobs also?
Oh, yeah, jobs are really, we're up 8,500 jobs right at this time in the woodlands.
I would say our percentage is pretty good.
I don't know exactly.
We relate percentage of people living in the woodlands.
We have 11,000 households in the woodlands.
We've got 8,600 jobs.
That's not bad.
We hope to have eventually a percentage of 100,000 jobs, 150,000 people, so the percentage is not too far from the original concept.
But if you're asking whether the Woodlands has 8.8% of the Houston job market, is that what your question is?
Oh, no, we don't have that.
No, we don't have that.
A new growth we may have, you see.
But our growth is of 8.8% of new housing, not resale housing.
And I'm not so sure of our jobs are picked up from
7,000, 8,500 the last couple of years, so I don't know what that percentage is compared to total job pick-up.
Houston total job pick-up has been about 60,000 a year for the last two years, so if you took 8% of that, that would be about, I'm not so sure, we're pretty close to that.
If we went from 7,000 to 8,500 jobs,
And a Houston pick-up of jobs was about $50,000, $60,000 one year, and $40,000 the other day, $100,000, and 8% of that would be $800,000.
So we picked up more than that.
We picked up more than that.
So your rate is ahead of the Houston rate.
Our rate, our ratio probably is ahead of the Houston ratio.
I'm just going to give you a guess.
I'd like to run the numbers for you, but that's a guess.
So that's working pretty well.
But we have built an opportunity for different types of jobs.
Office space, high technology, service industries.

therefore these and working with use advanced research center to figure out how the fallout could be on that how we work with venture capital coming which we helped defend someone here so it's all all in here that you don't find it clear lake you don't find it one colony you don't find the rest and you don't find it come up you don't find it west lake you don't find urban now that's that's why it's different then the key to the woodland is the beauty that we're able to preserve so far that i think is why people
I keep saying, gee, it's the best place I've ever lived.
Well, no, no, but the social structure for the kids have been good.
The hike and bike trail, we've got over 65 miles now.
I think of hike and bike trails in the woodlands, et cetera.
And those are things that.
Have there been any surprises along the way in terms of the social structures and in terms of the business developments?
Well, I think that the church has done a good job through the interfaith group.
We've had an amazing reaction among
the church groups that come into Woodlands, they all help each other get started.
It's really worked better than I thought.
We thought about ecumenical churches to begin with.
Well, you'll notice in the book, we felt that wouldn't work.
Churches this competitive is like people are.
But what has happened, the Native faith has worked with them.
We have some 20 churches or so here now.
There's been sharing of facilities.
Sharing of facilities.
And yet, as they get bigger, it's going to get more difficult, as you know, the whole thing.
I think that...
Yeah, there are a lot of surprises, like where we were disappointed when we had the University of Houston line up and come up with their north campus.
But we're going to get a rather reduced size north campus, because they couldn't get it over.
We've been sitting out there waiting for 20 years now.
And when I first went through the wood in the 69 with them, where they said, OK, we'll make a deal with you.
The boarding board said you'll have a south campus, which was going to be Clear Lake, and a north campus.
Well, they backed off now when they took the downtown campus on it.
They said, well, that's your other campus.
I heard us, you see.
So, however, we're going to get something out of it.
Has the transfer of authority to the local community gone pretty much according to the?
I would say it hadn't gone to us.
We still control the WCA.
However, we lose control in 92.
I'd say if one thing that we wish we'd have done better is that since our pace is not as what it was, I would have liked to have had another 10 years
to have control of the WCA, but we think we can work with them.
We work with Conroe and Montgomery County.
We can work with them as long as you do a good job.
And I think that they should be watchdogs of what's best for the community.
Oh, that's one of the brilliant things that was done is the fact that impregnated into the social structure is, in fact, the values, the philosophical values of the Woodlands.
Because as I've talked to various individuals, one of the questions I've asked is,
what happens when the hand of George Mitchell is not on the helm?
How will this continue?
And everyone says, it won't continue.
It's not a problem.
Yeah, really, they've been indoctrinated pretty well.
And I think it's worked real well.
As you get up to 100,000 people, I can't predict what will happen.
But I do think that if you go to 6 million people in Houston region, which it will in the next 25 years.
In fact, we even tried thinking about back

late 69, 70, working with Ann McCarg, who did our environmental planning, to do what I call the String of Pearls, where we would really have five projects similar with a different size, different character, within all of the beauty of southern Montgomery County and the city here.
So you think that might be a future for the... No, no, we're still working on it.
But I gave up when things got tough.
I didn't have time for it.
But we, McCarg and I, worked on the idea, and he wanted to do it.
So we now have our people looking at what would be like for wood trace.
We're getting ready to do one now.
They're compact, 2,800 acres.
A bit different, 1,800 acres.
You'll never do 125,000 acres again.
I don't know who could put this block together.
300 transactions put the block together.
So the string of pearls still has a lot of interest to me.
How do you really make the whole 6 million people work together and have transportation and have the orientation that makes it work better than what's going on in the rest of the country?
That's interesting.
One thing you're saying, too, is the future for the Woodlands Corporation far beyond the Woodlands.
Far beyond the Woodlands.
I'm thinking about all of Houston.
And really, I'm thinking about urbanization in the country.
Not only this state, but all other states.
You think about why do you have the horrible mess you have in New York City with 100 political subdivisions or Washington or Detroit?
We might be able to avoid that if we work together.
And you may not.
What we think would be wrong, because there'd be a lot of other things that come up that we never saw for some.
But I do think the idea of how you really urbanize better, if you think people are all going to move inside the loop in Houston, I don't believe that.
Because if you offer all this opportunity of job base and everything else, and yet tie into the cultural base, or the airport base, or the port base, that's what I think you have to do.
And then we argue about trying to match transit now.
But the mass transit used to know how to think about the overall plan, not just go from the Galleria downtown, which is ridiculous.
Two billion dollars, or a billion and one, they ought to go to the hospital.

But then how do you really tie the six billion people you're going to have together with commuter things and then inline rails, I mean, to the airport certainly and a few other places, or maybe Galleria then.
But how do you look at the whole?
And they're not looking at that whole.
It bothers me.
I'm on the executive committee.
I fought hard to do it a different way, but we've had one.
But you don't have to have light rail as time goes on.
I agree with that, the rail.
And with the mobility of the freeway systems, and the world is just part of it.
So my concern is that how do we urbanize 6 million people?
How do you do a better job than the rest of the country?
So I think that's a good example of just being an example.

For the next, let's sort of project ahead, for the next five years, ten years, and so forth, where do you see the main focus of your activities and the Woodlands activities, say, in the next five years?
I notice you're building 970 new units, housing units?
Yeah, we leave the town area, leave this area.
I would say this, that we're concentrating on the
residential, but I think now we're beginning to come alive at the high-tech area.
The search forests are looking very promising.
Also, the idea that I think the commercial is going to begin to build this way, because it follows the people.
Office space will begin to build this way.
There'll be more headquarter companies coming here with quality of life.
And that all should happen within the next five years.
You see a lot.
That's right.
We see a lot of that.
We think that we begin to see we're going to get the mall put together, we hope, in the next six months or so to get the mall started.
We see additional offers.
Right now, you cannot bill an office building at what price they'll offer you.
There's no billing unless you can afford to build a new one.
But that's getting to the point now where it's just about to break over.
So we'll get more of that.
Our apartments are very hot.
Our apartments are 95% leased up.
We're going to do more apartments.
To get to 54,000 units, you have to do more cluster housing, townhouses and apartments, and still preserve 7,000 acres of the Greenbelts.
And the thing is that, so those are things that I think the next five and ten years should begin to show, well, this project is really going to be economically viable.
People certainly doubt it, and still, it's doing well on land development, but still all the infrastructure has to show it makes economic viability, you see.
So we think that we do.
And then, mainly, also working with the 32,000 people in the 40,000 and 50,000.
How do you really work the relation of what we're trying to do to have it keep going on and yet correct something that we know we've done wrong?
Do you think simply the shared growth is going to markedly alter the complexion of the women?
I think it changes the complexion.
But what's really happened in the last 10 years, we didn't predict.
We created the Houston Advanced Research Center.
I thought I'd have a University of Houston site.
I didn't get that one.
OK, so that was one of the surprises that came along.
But then we decided to say an intellectual center is still going to be an intellectual center.
So we worked the Houston Advanced Research.
And when I got all four universities to work with us, we're not teasing whether or not they do the research.
So our research ambition has really, really skyrocketed.
Because I think the technology transfer is so important for the future of the state.
When we say, well, depletion and land depletion can't sustain the whole state, we'd better get better adapted to get your technology into the marketplace, which is what the park is supposed to do.
So maybe this is a richer and more unique environment than the one you originally conceived of in terms of academics.
I think it will be.
I would say that if you're not careful, it would be an elitist environment.
You don't want to talk completely, you see.
So you want to be sure that you have
As I say, the old cross-section of socioeconomic and ethnic mix as much as possible over a period of 50 years.
And therefore, we want the segment of it to be because that's it.
But then you've got to be careful it's not just strictly all of that, you see.
This string of pearls, as you mentioned, intrigued me a lot.
But obviously, there's going to be some differences, not just in size.
